Just got finished watching TAR. I've been watching it pretty much every night. It's really cool. Tonight they ended in Agra/New Delhi, India. Now, I've seen the show go to India in many other seasons, but none were like this. They portrayed India the right way. They showed a scarier side of the place. The teams were not ready for these people who didn't speak their language and the kids. OH. The kids. The kids would just drag themselves onto the contestants asking for money. And there's this shot of a tiny kid, couldn't've been older than 6 holding a baby walking down a highway to the travelers. And the teams were frantic, and I don't blame them. It's hard enough for them to do that stuff on very little sleep and extreme jet lag, but to do it in extremely populated India, yeah. It's hard. It was just a huge difference from when TAR7 went to India and the people loved all the teams and were helpful and really really nice. It was strange. Maybe it was that they were in a different place.

I should get kicking on these damn AP projects and GET TICKETS TO FUCKING CALIFORNIA.

Apparently, I'm not traveling alone like last time. I'm probably going to think of these flights as so short ever since being on Germany (and I even thought those were pretty short). 

Good travels to me!

FBI TEST 

The FBI had an opening for an assassin. After all the background checks, interviews and testing were done there were 3 finalists. Two men and a woman. For the final test, the FBI agents took one of the men to a large metal door and handed him a gun. 

"We must know that you will follow your instructions no matter what the circumstances. Inside the room you will find your wife sitting in a chair. Kill Her!!!" The man said, "You can't be serious! I could never shoot my wife." The agent said, "Then you're not the right man for this job. Take your wife and go home." 

The second man was given! the same instructions. He took the gun and went into the room. All was quiet for about 5 minutes. The man came out with tears in his eyes, "I tried, but I can't kill my wife." The agent said, "You don't have what it takes. Take your wife and go home." 

Finally, it was the woman's turn. She was given the same instructions, to kill her husband. She took the gun and went into the room. Shots were heard, one after another. They heard screaming, crashing, banging on the walls. After a few minutes, all was quiet. The door opened slowly and there stood the woman, She wiped the sweat from her brow. "This gun is loaded with blanks" she said. "I had to beat him to death with the chair." 
MORAL: Women are evil. Don't mess with them.

It hurts to listen. I don't think the cover is easily accessable, but it should be somewhere. It was from one of her concerts. Owch. Just awful.

I guess this would be an appropriate place to post pictures of Germany. There isn't exactly a community dedicated to the country, just ones for the language.
Ah. The river Neckar. This picture was taken from one of the many fortresses in the area. This is the famous old bridge of Heidelberg, the city is amazingly beautiful. This is from the the main street of Speyer. I unfortunately forgot the name of this small town that lays on the Nekar, but yet again this is taken from atop a very old fortress. This is the cathedral of Speyer. I have many pictures of inside the cathedral. It's awesome to go in there and see the crypts of the kings. So old, so cool.
I have more pictures. Namely of the Heidelberg Schloss. The area was just great. I wish I would have taken pictures of this wonderful city built on top of a hill. I can't wait to go back. It's only been a month since I left.

Also, my sister mentioned at dinner that there is now a large sign devoted to Sarah Floyd in our office. Considering we know most about Sarah, having her almost as a sibling in our house for two years, we're pretty sure that she is in El Salvador. Sending her good mojo. The sign explains her 'disappearence'. I don't think she'll be back for awhile. I'm not really sure I'll ever see her either. I don't know if I should email Mrs. Madigan, Sarah's favorite teacher and old JJW special ed teacher. Hm.

Eh. My switching to German apparently has caused controversy with my father and sister. My father thinks I'm stupid for doing it. As does my sister (we all know where she gets her opinions from). Why? Apparently Spanish will be taking over the USA in a couple years and I will rot in a burning mexicano hell while this happens. My father/sister seem to think the English language will be lost forever which would be a major let down to the rest of the world as well as us. I have nothing against the Spanish language, it's just not for me. Alot of people (especially from here where Spanish speakers are rare) forget their Spanish after high school. My sister shouldn't have any room to talk, her grades for spanish are good (I think), but she can't speak a word of the language. I know she can't understand native speakers or fast speakers either. For her, it's just an easy class where you listen to people talk. Even if I don't use German for alot of my life, at least I'll have the chance to know an interesting language that contributed to our own language (not saying spanish didn't, but I don't think it did as greatly, correct me if I'm wrong.). Plus, German is on the dark side... they have cookies.

Downtown Heidelberg, old bridge. Nice scenery. The river Neckar. It's great to have this view from this fortress on top of a hill. Nice reward for the climb up.
Oh don't worry kids, there are plenty more where that came from. Just not now.

Dinner Sister: I love the Lutenant governor, he was so cool. I hope he gets elected in two years. He has the same political views as I do. Me: Oh, they're re-electing Hitler? I missed the memo. Yea. Anyway, got back last night around two. Ms. Salo is telling me not to worry.. and I'm not. I'm going to do all the work thrown at me. Eh. I'll update later. Damn Europop.

Today we went to the Schloss of Heidelburg. It's great and I took plenty of pictures of the castle as well as the city. It was a nice relaxing day with alot of European in it (the weather too). Then I get home and read my Email. Thanks Ms. Salo, I love being told to do an essay as well as read 3 chapters in a textbook while taking notes. BUT I did sign up for an AP class and I wasn't expecting it to be easy, so I'm not upset, but I am alittle crazy over getting my work done. I think I'm going to finish up the Driver's Ed and Alg. 2 on Wednsday, and do the Essay tomorrow. I think I'll finish the essay pretty fast since I'm on a computer and I'll get the Algebra 2 done. The plane ride home will be reserved for my APWH reading and note taking. Then when I get home I'll have to do the English and whatever small amount of biology she gave me. Monday I have PE. Eh. Yay? oh well. Europe was far more worth it than missing everything. And if I do suffocate from all the papers that will be pushed at me on Monday, I'll die in peace. Sonia knows what I'm going to get...
Today is my aunt's party. Hmm.. it's typical European cloudy and rainy, but I like it.

Woo. Ok, I'm feeling great now (probably because of the aspirin, but oh well). We went to the Schwetsingen (or Schwetsinger, Schwetsing, whatever they call it.. everyone says something different) Schloss today, but they were expensive and timely (plus the tours were in German.. so). I swear, if we stayed here for a month, we'd be fluent. Sorry to you guys in Virginia if I get back and am still answering with Ja or Nein and saying Entschuldigung and Danke, remind me which country I'm in. We ate at the Italian restaurant with more liquor. I had a pizza. Nice place. I don't know though, we should be going to France sometime (I know, Three countries in two weeks). God, but I can't get that video and song from Rammstein out of my head. Sonia, you should download the song, but the video is just interestingly enjoyable. People, I'll be on AIM for awhile.
